{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617146"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:10:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16458"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16458"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.91,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75119"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60627"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8414"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"},{"type":"tags","id":"8539"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21734"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75119"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlial cells are essential components of the central nervous system, with distinct morphological features that can be identified through microscopy and specific staining techniques.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological appearance of astrocytes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Large cells with prominent Nissl substance","Small round cells with dense nuclei and scant cytoplasm","Star-shaped cells with multiple processes and GFAP-positive staining","Oval cells with lipid-rich cytoplasm","Elongated cells with myelin processes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological identification of different cell types in the central nervous system is crucial for understanding both normal and pathological processes. \u003Cstrong\u003EStar-shaped cells with multiple processes and GFAP-positive staining\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes astrocytes. These cells are characterised by their distinctive stellate morphology and express glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP), which is a specific marker used to identify astrocytes in histological preparations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options describe other neural cell types:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall round cells with dense nuclei and scant cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E describes oligodendrocyte precursor cells or lymphocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElongated cells with myelin processes\u003C/strong\u003E describes oligodendrocytes, which produce myelin in the central nervous system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge cells with prominent Nissl substance\u003C/strong\u003E describes neurons, which contain rough endoplasmic reticulum (Nissl substance)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOval cells with lipid-rich cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E describes activated microglial cells, the resident macrophages of the central nervous system\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAstrocytes play crucial roles including providing structural support, maintaining the blood-brain barrier, and responding to injury through reactive astrogliosis. During central nervous system injury, astrocytes undergo morphological changes and increase GFAP expression as part of the healing response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Astrocytes are star-shaped glial cells with multiple processes that express glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP).","Astrocytes provide structural and metabolic support to neurons and help maintain the blood-brain barrier.","Reactive astrogliosis is a hallmark response to central nervous system injury."],"references":["Sofroniew MV, Vinters HV. Astrocytes: biology and pathology. Acta Neuropathol. 2010 Jan;119(1):7-35. doi: 10.1007/s00401-009-0619-8. Epub 2009 Dec 10. PMID: 20012068; PMCID: PMC2799634.","Barsanti S, Viana JF, Veiga A, Machado JL, Abreu DS, Dias JD, Monteiro S, Silva NA, Pinto L, Oliveira JF. Assessing Different Histological Preparations for Reconstruction of Astrocyte Tridimensional Structure. Cells. 2024 Jun 3;13(11):969. doi: 10.3390/cells13110969. PMID: 38891101; PMCID: PMC11171983.","Sidoryk-Wegrzynowicz M, Wegrzynowicz M, Lee E, Bowman AB, Aschner M. Role of astrocytes in brain function and disease. Toxicol Pathol. 2011 Jan;39(1):115-23. doi: 10.1177/0192623310385254. Epub 2010 Nov 12. PMID: 21075920; PMCID: PMC6218934."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60627"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16458"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60627"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T23:06:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T23:07:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9149"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75119"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta"